I checked each round-1 finding against the canonical fresh render, `paper/index.qmd`, `paper/references.bib`, `SOURCES.md`, `data/parameters.yaml`, and the cited sources. The response marks all nine citation findings adopted; none of this referee's findings was declined or deferred.

## Resolution of round-1 findings

| Round-1 finding | Status | Note |
|---:|---|---|
| 1 | **RESOLVED** | The abstract now says one-third of 2025 U.S. megagift *value*, and the introduction gives the supported $6.65B/$19.2B comparison with Giving USA/AP while reserving CNBC for Yield Giving's $7.17B annual total; CNBC's author and title are corrected. |
| 2 | **RESOLVED** | The text now separates Miller et al.'s ACA-expansion mortality design from Sommers's cost–benefit reanalysis of pre-ACA expansions and cites Finkelstein for the OHIE spending component. |
| 3 | **PARTIALLY RESOLVED** | GiveWell (2024) is now attached only to its actual 3–4× re-evaluation, and 20–40× is labeled model arithmetic, but the paper still shows neither the cash-to-QALY input nor the arithmetic producing that range; `data/parameters.yaml` contains related assumptions but does not transparently reproduce the manuscript's 20–40× interval. |
| 4 | **PARTIALLY RESOLVED** | The cited GiveWell impact page does support “several hundred million dollars” of annual recommended grants and explains marginal funding, but it does not establish that funding beyond identified room converges to cash-transfer cost-effectiveness or that the multiple remains large under *any* diminishing-returns account consistent with the benchmarks. Those remain portfolio-scale scenario claims. |
| 5 | **PARTIALLY RESOLVED** | The false “common set of conventions” description has been replaced by an accurate adult/child/direct-anchor split, but the manuscript still gives no in-text support for the 26-year/0.78 adult calibration, the 65-year/0.87 child calibration, or the normative 3% rate; the parameter file itself labels the child figures author calibration and supplies no authoritative child sources. |
