@@ -0,0 +1,20 @@
+# Citations referee report — round 3
+
+## Resolution of outstanding round-2 items
+
+| Round-2 item | Status | Note |
+|---|---|---|
+| Finding 3 | **PARTIALLY RESOLVED** | The 20–40× cash-transfer comparison remains correctly labeled as model arithmetic, but the manuscript still does not show the cash-to-QALY input or the short calculation producing the interval. The repository documents related inputs, so this is a transparency issue rather than a false attribution. |
+| Finding 4 | **PARTIALLY RESOLVED** | The closing claim is now appropriately limited to scales “the cited benchmarks speak to.” However, “funding beyond identified room drives toward cash-transfer cost-effectiveness” still goes beyond what the cited GiveWell pages establish; they support declining marginal cost-effectiveness and the cash benchmark, not that particular convergence path. |
+| Finding 5 | **PARTIALLY RESOLVED** | The adult 26-year/0.78 and child 65-year/0.87 calibrations and the 3% rate remain uncited in the manuscript. `SOURCES.md` now makes the adult anchors and author-calibrated status of the child inputs reasonably auditable, which is adequate supporting documentation for a working paper, but one compact in-text citation or explicit “author calibration” label would be clearer. |
+| Finding 7 | **PARTIALLY RESOLVED** | The results section accurately identifies the HHS-recommended distribution and Table 3. The paper still omits the CPI adjustment from constant 2025 dollars to May-2026 dollars, and the conclusion still broadens the source to “the government's own regulatory valuation.” The parameter documentation supplies the conversion, but the conclusion should say “the HHS regulatory-analysis valuation used here.” |
+| Finding 9 | **PARTIALLY RESOLVED** | The sentence remains unchanged. Ord supports large cross-intervention cost-effectiveness differences, but not the appended claim that the cheapest health is not bought “where most philanthropic dollars are spent.” That clause should be separately sourced or presented as the paper's interpretation rather than as part of the Ord attribution. |
+| New finding 1 | **RESOLVED** | The AP reference now correctly names Rasheeda Childress and uses the displayed title and 2026 date. |
+| New finding 2 | **PARTIALLY RESOLVED** | The GiveWell, Robin Hood, Constellation Fund, and CEGA years now match the pages' publication/update dates. The CEGA entry still credits the institution although the page identifies Sam Fishman as the author; change the author to Fishman (with CEGA as publisher/site). |
+| New finding 3 | **RESOLVED** | The text now accurately says “a child-targeted cash quasi-experiment” for Aizer et al. and describes the additional designs as catalogued in the parameter file. |
+
+## New findings
+
+None. A brief regression check found no missing bibliography keys, uncited bibliography entries, unresolved citation markers, or newly broken attribution in the latest edits.
+
+RECOMMENDATION: Minor revisions

